+## 📌 CVE-2026-53461 – False Positive (Debian Bookworm)
+
+### Summary
+
+* **Issue:** Out-of-bounds heap **write** in the ICON decoder, leading to a crash (DoS)
+* **Component:** `coders/icon.c` — function `Read1XImage()` (the **legacy "Windows 1.0 Icon"** reader)
+* **Upstream fix:** ImageMagick6 commit [`b44b0a2`](https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick6/commit/b44b0a2443451ca8350513ca0f61b8d8846c87cd) — fixed in **6.9.13-50** / **7.1.2-25**
+* **Debian Bookworm ships:** `8:6.9.11.60+dfsg-*` (ImageMagick **6.9.11-60**)
+* **Verdict:** **False positive — vulnerable code is not present in this version**
+
+> ⚠️ **This is a different class of false positive than CVE-2023-34152 above.**
+> It is **not** about a disabled build feature or container runtime configuration.
+> The vulnerable function simply **did not exist yet** when 6.9.11-60 was released.
+> A scanner version-range match (`< 6.9.13-50`) flags it anyway.
+
+---
+
+### Root Cause of the Real Bug
+
+The one-line upstream fix is:
+
+```c
+-    for (y=0; y < (ssize_t) image->columns; y++)   /* BUG */
++    for (y=0; y < (ssize_t) image->rows; y++)      /* FIX */
+```
+
+This loop lives inside `Read1XImage()`, the reader for the **Windows 1.0 icon**
+format. That reader validates width and height **independently** as either `32`
+or `64`. For a non-square icon (e.g. **64 wide × 32 tall**):
+
+* The image buffer is allocated for `rows = 32` scanlines.
+* The faulty loop iterates `y` up to `columns = 64`.
+* For `y = 32 .. 63`, `QueueAuthenticPixels()` writes **past the end of the
+  pixel cache** → out-of-bounds heap write → crash.
+
+---
+
+### Why It Does Not Apply to 6.9.11-60 (Debian Bookworm)
+
+* The `Read1XImage()` function — and **Windows 1.0 Icon support in general** —
+  was introduced upstream on **2023-10-01** (commit *"support Windows 1.0 Icon
+  format"*).
+* ImageMagick **6.9.11-60** was released **2021-01-25**, roughly **2.5 years
+  earlier**. The buggy function never existed in this release.
+* In Bookworm's `coders/icon.c`, `ReadICONImage()` only accepts
+  `resource_type` 1 (ICO) and 2 (CUR) with BMP-style headers — there is **no
+  Windows 1.0 code path** and **no `Read1XImage` symbol**.
+* Every decode loop in the shipped file already bounds correctly on
+  `image->rows`, never `image->columns`:
+
+| Decode loop (icon.c) | Loop condition |
+| -------------------- | -------------- |
+| 1-bit / 4-bit / 8-bit / 16-bit / 24-32-bit / alpha-mask | `for (y = rows-1; y >= 0; y--)` ✅ |
+
+Verification commands (run against the Bookworm source):
+
+```bash
+# No vulnerable function present:
+grep -n "Read1XImage" coders/icon.c            # -> no output
+
+# No "y < columns" decode loop present:
+grep -n "y < (ssize_t) image->columns" coders/icon.c   # -> no output
+```
+
+Both return nothing, confirming the affected code is absent.
+
+---
+
+### Affected Debian Versions
+
+| Release    | Version   | Status                                              |
+| ---------- | --------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
+| Bullseye   | 6.9.11.60 | ❌ False positive (code added after this release)    |
+| Bookworm   | 6.9.11.60 | ❌ False positive (code added after this release)    |
+| Trixie/Sid | 7.x       | ⚠️ Verify per package version (≥ 7.1.2-25 is fixed) |
+
+---
+
+### Why You Should NOT "Backport" or Patch This
+
+* There is **no corresponding line to change** — the function being patched
+  does not exist in 6.9.11-60.
+* Touching the existing (already-correct) `rows` loops would **introduce a
+  regression**, not fix anything.
+* No rebuild of `libMagickCore` / `libMagickWand` is warranted.
+
+---
+
+### VEX / Scanner Disposition
+
+* **Status:** `not_affected`
+* **Justification:** `vulnerable_code_not_present`
+* **Impact statement:** The vulnerable `Read1XImage()` Windows 1.0 Icon reader
+  was introduced after the 6.9.11-60 release shipped in Debian Bookworm; the
+  affected code path cannot be reached.
+
+---
+
+### ✅ Conclusion
+
+* Not exploitable in Debian Bookworm (6.9.11-60) — affected code absent
+* Safe to treat as a **false positive**
+* No patching, backporting, or rebuilding required
+
+---
+
 ## Best Practice
 
 * Document the CVE as **non-impactful** in security reports
